title: Spring Awakening (not the play)
body:
wanted to bang this out cus its pride and im GAY !!!!!!!! very short but soft and thats what counts !!! pls rb if u like it-

Ship: Snufkin x Self Insert

Word Count: 396 

Warm, soft sunlight filtered through the trees, lighting the fresh leaves and glistening off melting snow. Birds twittered and squirrels chattered as they arose from their long winter rest. The inhabitants of Moominvalley had all realized that it was finally Spring.

All, except for one.

One boy still lay curled in his den, softly snoring away despite the warm Spring air. The thick covering of moss and dead leaves over the entrance to his den made sure that no light came through, and he wasn’t the type to wake along with his own internal clock. Especially not after the ruckus that had been caused by Little My and Moomin just days earlier; he always hated being woken up before Winter’s end.

As he was dreaming, the soft sound of a new tune worked its way into his fantasy. His ears twitched. No, it wasn’t just a part of his dream, he confirmed with a sleepy raise of his head and a small nip of his hand.

As the sound drew closer, he took the time to stretch out, rubbing the sleep from his eyes. He could definitely confirm, now, what exactly that sound was. A mouth organ.

His suspicions were confirmed as the soft music came to a stop just outside his den. There was a rustling of a camping backpack, and then the moss was being carefully moved aside. A familiar pair of emerald green eyes peered into the den, cautious at first, but relieved when they saw the occupant awake.

“Good morning.”

Calamus smiled and yawned in response, stretching again. “G’morning…” he muttered, voice still thick with sleep.

“How was your winter?”

He couldn’t help laughing softly, smiling to Snufkin. “Well, I wouldn’t know, considering I slept through most of it.”

Snufkin chuckled himself. “You make a good point.”

It was in that small lull in conversation that Calamus chose to move and hug Snufkin. He nestled into his chest, breathing in deep the lingering scents of the forest and pipe smoke that clung to his clothes.

After a moment, he lifted his head. Snufkin seemed nearly reluctant to do the same. “You’re on your way to see Moomintroll, I’m guessing?”

“Of course,” Snufkin nodded. “Would you like to come with?”

“I’d love to,” Calamus hummed.

It was the same answer, the same conversation every Spring, but it would never become any less special.

summary: So I’m reading Moomin Midsummer Madness now and it’s the one in which Snufkin has beef with a park keeper. However I noticed a...
body:
So I’m reading Moomin Midsummer Madness now and it’s the one in which Snufkin has beef with a park keeper. However I noticed a big difference between the way Moominvalley framed the narrative as opposed to the original novels.

In the show, Snufkin comes across the fence accidentally. He has no preexisting acquaintance with the park keeper and is mainly just annoyed by the notice boards and the fact that a part of the woods, which he just claimed belongs to everyone, is fenced off.

Later on that same day he meets Little My and she just happens to have the Hattifattener seeds, which sparks his idea of using them to scare the park keeper and get revenge. It being midsummer eve (the only night the Hattifatteners grow) is just a lucky coincidence and the plot is quite sudden and almost a momentary decision.

In the book, Snufkin also meets My but she didn’t have the seeds. He did. He had collected them sometime before the events of the book for the sole purpose of antagonizing the park keeper, with whom he has some kind of issue that is going on for a lot longer than we can probably tell. The plot is completely premeditated.

Not only that though: This was so important to Snufkin that he is purposefully late in coming back to the Valley, knowing it would upset Moomin, and even feeling bad about it. This more than anything should tell us how much he hates the park keeper and his signs… As he confirms himself a bit later

I don’t know, just thought that was an interesting change…
